<subSubSection id="C363652FFF5DBE97FF017385F459F932" pageId="185" pageNumber="772" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BC636A4FF5DBE97FF017385F364F94C" blockId="185.[242,1475,1514,1746]" pageId="185" pageNumber="772">
DESCRIPTION. — 
<emphasis id="B90DEAB6FF5DBE97FE4F7384F545F9E1" box="[444,620,1515,1538]" italics="true" pageId="185" pageNumber="772">Shell morphology</emphasis>
. Length 2.5 mm, width 1.8 mm (single specimen examined). Shell solid, oval, with convex sides, narrower posteriorly (Fig. 93I). Only 1 whorl visible, forming the entire shell. Apex rounded, depressed, slightly umbilicate (Fig. 93H), with the aperture lip rising slightly from the left side. Anterior end of the shell rounded. Umbilicus narrow. Aperture long, wide anteriorly, narrowing abruptly at about 1/2 of its length. Columellar margin slightly thickened. Sculpture of 8 irregular spiral grooves (Fig. 93J) near the posterior end and 12 near the anterior end, absent from the middle area of the shell. Colour uniformly whitish.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC636A4FF5DBE97FEE370D5F459F932" blockId="185.[242,1475,1514,1746]" box="[272,880,1722,1746]" pageId="185" pageNumber="772">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB6FF5DBE97FEE370D5F643F932" box="[272,362,1722,1745]" italics="true" pageId="185" pageNumber="772">Anatomy</emphasis>
. Unknown. All shells collected lacked soft parts.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C363652FFF5DBE94FF017090F6D9FE84" lastPageId="186" lastPageNumber="773" pageId="185" pageNumber="772" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BC636A4FF5DBE94FF017090F6D9FE84" blockId="185.[242,1474,1791,1850]" lastBlockId="186.[212,1444,266,359]" lastPageId="186" lastPageNumber="773" pageId="185" pageNumber="772">
REMARKS. — This species differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D27FF5DBE97FD62716FF418F8F4" authority="Valdés, 2008" authorityName="Valdés" authorityYear="2008" box="[657,817,1792,1815]" class="Gastropoda" genus="Micratys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cephalaspidea" pageId="185" pageNumber="772" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="wareni" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB6FF5DBE97FD62716FF418F8F4" box="[657,817,1792,1815]" italics="true" pageId="185" pageNumber="772">Micratys wareni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A23E57CDFF5DBE97FCC4716FF45BF8F4" box="[823,882,1792,1815]" pageId="185" pageNumber="772" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D27FF5DBE97FC8E716FF3BAF8F4" authority="Habe, 1952" authorityName="Habe" authorityYear="1952" box="[893,1171,1791,1815]" class="Gastropoda" genus="Micratys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cephalaspidea" pageId="185" pageNumber="772" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="ovum">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB6FF5DBE97FC8E716FF338F8F4" box="[893,1041,1792,1815]" italics="true" pageId="185" pageNumber="772">Micratys ovum</emphasis>
Habe, 1952
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D27FF5DBE97FB3B716FF271F8F4" box="[1224,1368,1791,1815]" class="Gastropoda" genus="Micratys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cephalaspidea" pageId="185" pageNumber="772" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="undefined-1">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB6FF5DBE97FB3B716FF237F8F4" box="[1224,1310,1792,1815]" italics="true" pageId="185" pageNumber="772">Micratys</emphasis>
sp. 
<quantity id="4C819B41FF5DBE97FAB97090F271F8F4" box="[1354,1368,1791,1815]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.54" pageId="185" pageNumber="772" unit="in" value="1.0">1</quantity>
</taxonomicName>
in having an oval shell with the anterior end shorter and more rounded. It is likely that it is an undescribed species, but it is not named here because of the lack of anatomical information. It is provisionally placed in the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D27FF5EBE94FB017764F261FEC1" authorityName="Habe" authorityYear="1952" box="[1266,1352,267,290]" class="Gastropoda" genus="Micratys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cephalaspidea" pageId="186" pageNumber="773" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB6FF5EBE94FB017764F261FEC1" box="[1266,1352,267,290]" italics="true" pageId="186" pageNumber="773">Micratys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because of the presence of a small apical perforation, a well-developed umbilicus and spiral striations near the anterior and posterior ends of the shell.
</paragraph>
